A basic C++ program has a specific structure that must be followed.

**Basic Program Structure:**
```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  // Your code here
  cout << "Hello, World!" << endl;
  return 0;
}
```

**Breakdown:**
- `#include <iostream>` - Includes input/output library
- `using namespace std;` - Uses standard namespace
- `int main()` - Main function (entry point)
- `{ }` - Code block
- `cout` - Output stream
- `return 0;` - Returns success status

**Comments:**
```cpp
// Single-line comment

/* Multi-line
   comment */
```

**Compilation:**
```bash
g++ program.cpp -o program
./program
```

C++ uses streams for input and output operations.

**Output (cout):**
```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  cout << "Hello, World!" << endl;
  cout << "Age: " << 25 << endl;
  cout << "Name: " << "John" << endl;
  return 0;
}
```

**Input (cin):**
```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  int age;
  string name;

  cout << "Enter your name: ";
  cin >> name;

  cout << "Enter your age: ";
  cin >> age;

  cout << "Hello " << name << ", you are " << age << endl;
  return 0;
}
```

**getline for Strings:**
```cpp
string fullName;
cout << "Enter your full name: ";
getline(cin, fullName); // Reads entire line
```

**Escape Sequences:**
- `\n` - New line
- `\t` - Tab
- `\\` - Backslash
- `\"` - Double quote
